ure and other national literatures, particularly that of France. A selected bibliography suggests sources for further reading. No study of French-Canadian literature can be completely without reference to the rich and diverse body of criticism that has developed along with it. This is a unique introduction for English-speaking readers, one that should be required reading for all courses in Canadian literature and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriticismzQuébec (Province). 0aCriticismzQuébec (Province). 0aFrench-Canadian literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Political Parties.2bisacsh1 aAquin, Hubert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBessette, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrault, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberland, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEthier-Blais, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalardeau, Jean-Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrancoeur, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayne, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLalonde, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcotte, Gilles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShouldice, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757486440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487574864423Coveruhttps://www.degru